  "answer": "The corpus contains the Vīramitrodaya (work_slug: unknown-viramitrodaya-d4b632) but does not include a direct, explicit definition of nibandha as a genre. However, the text itself—and the pattern of citation within it—makes the genre characteristics clear.\n\nA nibandha (literally 'digest' or 'compilation') is a medieval Sanskrit genre of dharmaśāstra literature in which a scholar systematically collects, organizes, and synthesizes quotations from authoritative earlier sources—smṛtis, śrutis, Purāṇas, and older nibandhas—on a specific topic or set of topics related to dharma. Rather than presenting original doctrine, a nibandha author marshals the views of recognized authorities, resolves apparent contradictions among them, and arranges this material topically to provide a comprehensive practical guide. The genre flourished from roughly the 11th–17th centuries CE and served to make the enormous and sometimes conflicting body of dharmic literature accessible in organized form.\n\nThe Vīramitrodaya exemplifies the nibandha genre in the following ways:\n\n1. Commissioned topical compilation: Composed by Mitra Miśra at the command of King Vīrasiṃha (of the Bundela dynasty) in Vārāṇasī, the work is described in its own colophon as 'the great sunrise for the lotus of smṛti' and as a work 'composed of sacred injunctions, a mirror to the world of ritual action' (ch.1, p-eabeb6). It is explicitly a synthesis, not an original treatise.\n\n2. Systematic topical organization: The Samayaprakāśa section (the portion present in this corpus, dealing with ritual time) walks through every tithi (lunar day), festival, season, and occasion in strict sequence—determining the correct time for each rite by reference to smṛti authority.\n\n3. Citation of multiple authoritative sources: The opening of the Samayaprakāśa states that Mitra Miśra 'having taken to heart the entire meaning declared by the sages Hārīta, Gobhila, Parāśara, Nārada, and others' composed the work (p-9029cc). Throughout, he quotes smṛti verses and resolves conflicts among them.\n\n4. Citation of earlier nibandhas: The text itself cites other nibandha works—the Jyotirnibandha (p-d87bf0) and the Sūryodaya-nibandha in the Bhārgavārcanadīpikā (p-b04cf2)—demonstrating the genre's self-referential, cumulative character.\n\n5. Encyclopedic scope: The table of contents for the Samayaprakāśa alone (p-fc3a75 onward) lists dozens of subtopics—years, solstices, seasons, every tithi from Pratipad to Pañcadaśī, major festivals, eclipses, intercalary months, ancestral rites, cosmic ages, and more—showing the comprehensive, digest-like ambition of the genre.\n\nIn short: nibandha is a genre of organized dharmic digest that aggregates authoritative quotations by topic; the Vīramitrodaya exemplifies it as a multi-volume thematic compilation synthesizing smṛti and śruti sources on all aspects of dharma and kāla (time), composed under royal patronage by a learned Brahmin scholar.",
